<taxonomicName id="3577A34E2478CCA29295579DF9A18895" LSID="93D7D7AA-9D4A-5C37-B890-7589A20E1624" authority="(Poli, 1791)" baseAuthorityName="Poli" baseAuthorityYear="1791" class="Bivalvia" family="Sphaeriidae" genus="Pisidium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pisidium casertanum" order="Sphaeriida" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="casertanum">Pisidium casertanum (Poli, 1791)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E356E39C31BAE0E12F9772DE43381338" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346" type="ecological interactions">
<paragraph id="859BA4E15D633EC2F7AD75424C70E107" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346">Ecological interactions</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FF9CE4FC107404C6033E3C98B619D2DA" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346" type="native status">
<paragraph id="F168701B856D81E43693EFBB43C695ED" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346">Native status</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC9FD8779539FD8B5AD0CCA2D47A514B" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346">Autochtonous</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="106BD6611D998447E1EBDFA4AC2CF0A1" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="F4BEA4CEB8BDFB1AD1F1875F9FBEA544" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D3DC5471BE5A9980B72D4E4D4B304610" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346">
Cosmopolitan. More widely present in the Northern Hemisphere than the Southern one where it is more limited to high altitudes localities (
<bibRefCitation id="340180F6BACCF02C9920653475CCACD5" author="Kuiper, J. G. J." journalOrPublisher="Basteria" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346" pagination="3 - 52" refId="B7406748" refString="Kuiper, J. G.J., 1983. The Sphaeriidae of Australia. Basteria 47: 3 - 52" title="The Sphaeriidae of Australia" volume="47" year="1983">Kuiper 1983</bibRefCitation>
). Widespread throughout Morocco.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0914ED36C91E7E0BC8707708CC297F65" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346" type="notes">
<paragraph id="04BD8C8244FDD8173E1B63D96449C992" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph id="914F685D19FB93FC2EA9ADD7143F6C9E" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346">
Shell dimensions: Mean length = 4.09 
<normalizedToken id="86F197C0F8009D69F4B399F9BB708275" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
0.7 mm; Mean height = 3.42 
<normalizedToken id="E0E53FC3290C08A76E07CB46B2298C10" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
0.59 mm; Mean width = 2.52 
<normalizedToken id="66A9C51E28D33875140102A6B8A6CC62" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
0.76 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="624FA33C8D9F78A3662F08B18002AFE6" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346">
Key features: Extremely variable, but can be separated from other species by its flattened umbo and shell (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5B9C9232C224F327FC4688A8E7792DDE" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F7408629" captionText="Figure 6. Pisidium casertanum from Ouzioua River a External view of the whole animal (left and right); b Dorsal view; c internal view of hinge plate of left and right valves." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e73346.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/577820" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346">6</figureCitation>
). Periostracum silky, coated with ferruginous deposits. The dorsal margin is relatively long. Cardinal teeth: C2 arched, C4 straight and short, C3 strongly curved, at times bifurcated posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EE78888F57F271C3F165643829D7EF96" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346">
Remarks: The species is known to be highly variable morphologically (
<bibRefCitation id="F1ED79DE842011BA512C182C27CBC867" author="Rassam, Hanane" journalOrPublisher="Malacologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346" refId="B7406537" refString="Rassam, Hanane, Albrecht, Christian, Sousa, Ronaldo, Lopes-Lima, Manuel, Benaissa, Hassan, Ghamizi, Mohamed, 2021. Intraspecific variation in the common pea clam, Pisidium casertanum (Poli, 1791) (Bivalvia: Sphaeriidae): A geometric morphometric analysis. Malacologia 63 (2)" title="Intraspecific variation in the common pea clam, Pisidium casertanum (Poli, 1791) (Bivalvia: Sphaeriidae): A geometric morphometric analysis" volume="63" year="2021">Rassam et al. 2021b</bibRefCitation>
). The different morphological forms that the species can take are related to the effect of habitat conditions (
<bibRefCitation id="6A6107CDAA9D00518796037AAA2EEA7D" author="Piechocki, A." journalOrPublisher="Annales Zoologici" pageId="0" pageNumber="73346" pagination="249 - 320" refId="B7407364" refString="Piechocki, A., 1989. The Sphaeriidae of Poland (Bivalvia, Eulamellibranchia). Annales Zoologici 24: 249 - 320" title="The Sphaeriidae of Poland (Bivalvia, Eulamellibranchia)." volume="24" year="1989">Piechocki 1989</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
